ame <i>Dietmar</i> (see   Dittmar  ) or   Tiedemann  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dittmar","meanings":["from <i>þeud</i> ‘people’ + <i>māri</i> ‘famous’; as <i>Theodemar(us)</i> the name of two 12th-century saints: a missionary to the Wends and an archbishop of Salzburg."]},{"name":"Tumey","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of German <b>Tümme</b>: variant of   Thieme  , or a nickname from Middle High German <i>tumbe</i> ‘dumb, inexperienced, naive, mute’. The surname <i>Tümme</i> is very rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Thiem","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Kurt, Reinhardt.","German: variant of   Thieme  , a cognate of 2 below.","Dutch: from a pet form of an ancient Germanic name formed with <i>theod</i> ‘people, race’ + a second element beginning with <i>m-</i>, as in <i>Dietmar</i> (see   Dittmar  ) or   Tiedeman  ."]},{"name":"Timken","meanings":["North German: variant of   Thieme  ."]}]},{"name":"the","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a variant spelling of   Ty   or a transferred use of the surname, a local name for someone who lived by a common pasture, Middle English <i>tye</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Second","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of French   Sicard  , reflecting the characteristic Canadian and American French rounding of the <i>-ard</i> ending. Compare   Secor   and   Sicord  .","History: The Secords are descendants of Ambroise Sicard, a Huguenot refugee from France (see   Sicard  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Sicard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adrien, Albertine, Aude, Benoit, Camille, Elzear, Francois, Jacques, Jean-Paul, Marcel, Monique, Numa.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sighard</i>, composed of the elements <i>sig</i> ‘victory’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’. Compare   Seacord  ,   Secor  ,   Secord  ,   Secore  ,   Secoy  , and   Sicord  .","History: Jean Sicard from Mornac-sur-Seudre in Charente-Maritime, France, married Catherine Lauzon in Montreal, QC, in 1681. Jean-Baptiste Sicard, <i>sieur</i> de Carufel (see   Carufel  ), from Castres in Tarn, France, married Geneviève Raté in Saint-Pierre, Île d'Orléans, QC, in 1694. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered forms <i>Sicord</i> and <i>Seacord</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America. The Huguenot ancestor was Ambroise Sicard from France, who arrived with his wife and children in NY in the 1680s via England. His descendants (also) bear the surnames <i>Seacord</i>, <i>Secor</i>, <i>Secord</i>, and <i>Secoy</i>."]}]},{"name":"in","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the numerous girls' names ending in these two syllables (representing a Latinate feminine suffix), for example <i>Christina</i> and <i>Georgina</i>. It is now occasionally used as an independent given name.  See also  Ena ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"the","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a variant spelling of   Ty   or a transferred use of the surname, a local name for someone who lived by a common pasture, Middle English <i>tye</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thiemo the Second in the Quinziggau was born about 1015, in Hungary, his father, Count Dietmar Winzenburg of Quinziggau I, was 26 and his mother, Unknown, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Thiemo the Second. He died in 1064, at the age of 50."},"et":{"Abt 1015–       1064":"umbes 1015–1064","1015–1064":"1015–1064","1030–Female":"1030–Surnud","1050–1109":"1050–1109","0990–1040":"0990–1040","0990–Female":"0990–Surnud","1015":"1015","0990":"0990","      